<HL>
   Pathe Gives Data
   On Financing
   MGM/UA Buy-Out
   ----
   By Richard Turner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   PCC MGM TWX RANKY G.BRT
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- Pathe Communications Corp. provided new
details of how it proposes to finance its pending $1.2
billion acquisition of MGM/UA Communications Co.
   In an advertisement in some of yesterday's editions of
this newspaper, Pathe disclosed the names of several banks
and European companies that would be advancing money to
Comfinance S.A., a Luxembourg-based affiliate of Pathe
principal Giancarlo Parretti. Comfinance has agreed to
provide about $368 million toward the purchase price and Time
Warner Inc. has agreed to lend another $650 million. Pathe
has already deposited $200 million in cash toward the
acquisition.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Pathe said Banque Arabe et Internationale D'Investissement
would provide a $75 million one-week line of credit to
Comfinance and another $10 million credit line to a Pathe
affiliate. The Paris-based bank was created in 1973 with 50%
of its shares held by Arab banks and 50% held by non-Arab
financial institutions. It was one of several banks founded
during the 1970s to act as a conduit for the recycling of
petrodollars amassed by the Arab members of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries. Last month, state-owned
Banque Nationale de Paris said it would take control of the
troubled bank, which had been hobbled by the steep decline in
world crude oil prices during the latter half of the 1980s
and bad loans in developing countries.
   Another $50 million would come from an advance by
Amsterdam-based PAN-ASS B.V. in connection with a proposed
sale of certain Spanish assets by Comfinance to an affiliate
of PAN-ASS. Other sources of the financing are various asset
sales and $15 million under an existing $80 million credit
line from Credit Lyonnais Bank Nederland B.V., a well-known
entertainment industry lender. Another $91 million would be
advanced to a Pathe affiliate by Deepbridge B.V., Amsterdam.
Details about PAN-ASS and Deepbridge weren't available.
   Pathe also said it was in discussions with at least three
companies about acquiring an equity stake in MGM/UA after the
transaction closes, perhaps providing much-needed production
funds for the new company. They are Rank Laboratories Ltd.,
the film-processing unit of British-based Rank Organisation
PLC; RTL-Plus, a Luxembourg-based television company
39%-owned by West German media giant Bertelsmann AG, and
Cinergi Productions Inc., a Beverly Hills, Calif-based film
company formed by Andrew G. Vajna, a co-founder of Carolco
Pictures Inc. who sold his stake in the company early this
year for more than $100 million.
   The $20-a-share tender offer is scheduled to expire
Friday, but could be extended to June 23.
   MGM/UA shares were unchanged yesterday at $18.875 in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0153
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0153.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   The Locals Can Pick New Names,
   Like the Grand Ole Grocery Store
   ----
   By Keith L. Alexander
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<LP>
   RENFRO VALLEY, Ky. -- There's an identity crisis brewing
in this quiet backwater town 50 miles south of Lexington.
   The trouble began when a group of well-heeled investors
bought the trademarked and copyrighted property of the late
John Lair, who 51 years ago established the Renfro Valley
Barn Dance, Kentucky's version of the Grand Ole Opry.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The investors contend that the purchase gives them
exclusive use of the Renfro Valley name for a new $12 million
country-music theme park they're constructing. And to protect
their rights, the investors, Renfro Valley Folks Inc., have
told townspeople that only attractions associated with the
park may continue to use the name Renfro Valley.
   For the four existing businesses in town that already use
the name, that could mean drop it -- or else. The businessmen
say they've received a letter from the investor group
threatening legal action unless they change the name of their
stores and remove paraphernalia that displays the name Renfro
Valley.
   The businessmen, who have consulted a Washington, D.C.,
law firm, are steamed. "They didn't buy the whole valley,
they just bought a piece of it," snaps Willard Collinsworth,
the 64-year-old proprietor of the Renfro Valley Country
Store.
   And his wife, Aline, adds: "I think it's terrible. These
local businessmen have been here for many years, and now
these people are just coming in trying to take over. They
just don't care about the little people."
   Not true, says Ralph Gabbard, president of Renfro Valley
Folks. He contends that the whole town would benefit from the
project -- a 110-acre theme park that would be a sort of
cross between Opryland U.S.A. and Walt Disney World. Most
townspeople support the plan because of the jobs it would
bring.
   And though Mr. Gabbard promises to resolve the dispute in
a "peaceful way," he insists the businessmen are fighting a
losing battle.
   Maybe so. Joe Allen, owner of the Renfro Valley Record
Store, concedes that for the moment all the local businessmen
can do is "wait and worry." But while he initially painted
over the Renfro Valley in his store's name, he has now
restored the original wording.
   "They're multimillionaires. They intend on running us
little independent people out," Mr. Allen says, defiantly
adding: "We can't give in."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0152
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0152.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   USX Sells West German Unit
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
