<HL>
   International:
   Moscow Softens Line on Germany
   ---
   Gorbachev Drops Demand
   For Warsaw Pact Ties,
   Hints at Basis for Accord
   ----
   By Peter Gumbel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST EUROP
</CO>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   MOSCOW -- The Soviet Union continues to blow hot and cold
on the vexed question of German unity, but some clear signs
of flexibility are emerging from behind the rhetoric.
   Addressing the Soviet parliament, President Mikhail
Gorbachev gave his broadest hint so far that Moscow could
envisage certain conditions under which a united Germany
could be part of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization. Mr.
Gorbachev repeated an earlier Soviet formula that Germany
could become an "associate member" of both NATO and the
Warsaw Pact as long as this was done in conjunction with an
overhaul of the two military alliances as part of the German
unification process.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But in an apparent change from the earlier Soviet
position, Mr. Gorbachev dropped his insistence on East
Germany remaining part of the Warsaw Pact military structure.
Instead, he said that during a transition period, the West
German army would be subordinated to NATO, while the East
German army would be subject to the new government of a
united Germany -- not to the Warsaw Pact. The new German
government may well disband the East German army. However,
Soviet troops would continue to be stationed on East German
soil during the transition period, Mr. Gorbachev said.
   His comments were presented in a hypothetical way and
don't constitute any major breakthrough in solving the
problem of a future security arrangement for Germany. The
Soviet leader previously has suggested that U.S. and Soviet
troops should remain on German soil, and has frequently
called for major changes to the two military alliances.
   But Soviet officials and Western diplomats said Mr.
Gorbachev's comments are noteworthy because they signal a
strong desire by the Kremlin to work with NATO in the search
of a face-saving security arrangement for Germany. As such,
the comments represent a sharp turn from Moscow's tougher
stance just a few weeks ago, when it rejected German NATO
membership and suggested that German neutrality was the only
feasible option.
   "It's important not to read too much into the content {of
Mr. Gorbachev's remarks}," said one German diplomat. "But the
Soviets are sending a signal to the world that serves its own
function."
   In Washington, President Bush told reporters that the U.S.
hadn't changed its position that a unified Germany should be
in NATO with no conditions. In Brussels, NATO said in a
statement that it would study Gorbachev's speech carefully
but that the idea of duel or associate membership "does not
seem promising."
   The Soviet desire to reach a formula on German security
was underscored at a meeting between Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze and his West German counterpart, Hans-Dietrich
Genscher, in the Soviet town of Brest on Monday. Details of
the more than six hours of talks weren't disclosed. But Mr.
Shevardnadze told a concluding news conference that, "We see
the development of a very favorable setting for a mutually
acceptable settlement of the military-political status of a
future united Germany."
   Following the democratic revolution in East Germany last
fall, Moscow soon realized there was little it could do to
stop German unification. But, as one of the four victorious
World War II powers, it could still drag its feet and disrupt
the unification process. Many Soviet analysts say Moscow
would be unwise to do so because it would risk jeopardizing
relations with the new state from the start.
   But Mr. Gorbachev has been under strong pressure from
high-level Soviet officials, both civilian and military, over
how to handle the security issue. Many say publicly that a
united Germany as part of NATO would be a severe
foreign-policy blow, tantamount to "losing" East Germany.
   "There are numerous signs that NATO is using the new
situation on the continent to pursue its selfish aims,
creating an imbalance of forces," Oleg Baklanov, a senior
Communist Party official, told the Rabochaya Tribuna
newspaper. "Our Western partners would like to proceed from
premises that are advantageous only to them."
   The U.S. and its allies have tried to take such concerns
into account. At a recent NATO meeting in Scotland, U.S.
Secretary of State James Baker offered concessions that are
designed to make German membership of NATO more palatable to
the Soviets. But many in Moscow say that these moves don't go
far enough, and they are seeking to use the German issue as
leverage to bring about a fundamental change to the NATO
alliance.
   "We need a more solid basis {for a future security
arrangement for Germany} than NATO, which is built on
confrontation with the Soviet Union," says Valentin Falin, a
former Soviet ambassador to West Germany who now plays an
important role in formulating Moscow's German policies. He
says Mr. Baker's plans are "generally positive, but so far
they are only ideas."
   Mr. Gorbachev told parliament that, "We can't accept that
the West thinks movement should only come from our side."
   The issue is immensely complicated by the Soviet Union's
love-hate relationship with Germany. Many Soviets are looking
to Germany to provide badly needed economic assistance. There
are already strong rumors in Moscow and elsewhere that Bonn
is considering offering large government credits to the
Soviets, perhaps as the price for accepting East German
membership of NATO.
   But hardliners in the Kremlin also have a potent argument:
World War II, in which more than 20 million Soviets died.
They use the war to warn of the dangers of an enlarged
Germany and press home their arguments for tough terms
concerning a future security arrangement. "We can understand
the Germans, who have waited 45 years {for unity}," Mr. Falin
says. "But we should be aware of worries that the expansion
of Germany is linked with militarism. We must not forget the
lessons of the past."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0147
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0147.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Appeals Panel
   Negates SEC's
   Rule on Voting
   ---
   Agency Exceeded Its Powers
   By Having Firms Adopt
   `One Share, One Vote'
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- A federal appeals court panel struck down
the Securities and Exchange Commission's "one share, one
vote" rule, a move that could reshape the way some companies
protect themselves from takeovers.
   The panel, in a 3-0 decision, told the SEC that it had
overstepped its authority under federal securities law and
had entered corporate governance, an area traditionally
determined by state law. The court told the SEC that if the
rule were validated, "the commission would be able to
establish a federal corporate law by using access to the
national capital markets as its enforcement mechanism."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The ruling could encourage more companies to try to create
multiple classes of stock in efforts to help protect
incumbent management. Several lawyers and academics suggested
that the ruling is likely to help boost the role of "white
knights," who are often brought in by management to help fend
off hostile bidders. Those investors could get shares with
enhanced voting rights as part of their stake in a company.
   The SEC, which said it was "disappointed," hasn't decided
whether to appeal the ruling by a panel of the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia in favor of the Business
Roundtable, a group of 200 major corporations. The agency
could appeal either to the full appeals court or to the
Supreme Court. But the agency is likely to ask the exchanges
to adopt uniform voting procedures on their own, amending the
rules that way.
   Even if the appeals court ruling stands, it's unclear how
many companies would be able to get shareholder approval for
multiple classes of stock with unequal voting rights.
Institutional investors have emerged as a substantially more
active group in recent years and aren't likely to placidly
watch corporate managements take steps that could entrench
themselves.
   Dual voting is "clearly the most potent and ultimate
protective device because it does a lot more than prevent
hostile takeovers," said John Pound, finance professor at
Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government.
"Management is effectively insulated from unwanted changes."
   He said institutional investors, particularly public
employee funds that have been the most active in pressing
shareholder-rights issues, were likely to take a strong stand
against the introduction of new dual stock classes. "I think
this would generate real outrage among those institutions
concerned with good governance issues," he said. "That might
be a real restraint at major companies" tempted to introduce
new stock classes, he added.
   At the time the rule, called 19c4, was enacted by a 4-1
commission vote, 60 New York Stock Exchange companies had
disparate voting rights or planned to introduce them. In
addition, 182 companies on the National Association of
Securities Dealers automated quotation system and 117
American Stock Exchange concerns had such structures,
according to SEC figures.
   While those companies with two classes of stock already in
place were "grandfathered" and allowed to retain those
classes, the SEC rule said that companies couldn't in the
future abolish or reduce shareholder voting rights and remain
on an exchange or Nasdaq.
   By setting up the rule that way, the SEC tried to skirt
state corporate-governance problems because the agency
regulates the exchanges. But the appeals court rejected the
SEC argument, citing a 1977 Supreme Court ruling that said,
"we are reluctant to federalize the substantial portion of
the law of corporations that deals with transactions in
securities."
   The exchanges, led by the Big Board, will be watching the
SEC carefully. The New York exchange pressed the SEC for
rule-making help in 1988 when it was forced to reconsider an
exchange rule that prohibited multiple classes of stock. That
was during the takeover binge of the 1980s when a host of
companies were eager to protect themselves from corporate
raids.
   At the time, the Amex had a more permissive rule allowing
companies to list several classes of shares, and the Nasdaq
didn't have any rule governing the voting structure.
   After the SEC passed its rule, the exchanges adopted
similar rules. If the appeals court decision stands, the
exchanges will be forced to decide how to handle their own
rules.
   The Business Roundtable applauded the ruling. "American
shareholders won an important victory today," said Bruce
Atwater, chairman of the group's corporate governance task
force and chief executive officer of General Mills Inc. "The
court has resoundingly affirmed their right to determine for
themselves what kinds of equities best serve their
interests."
   But some observers said the ruling could hurt
shareholders. "It's hard to justify having national policy on
issues like this made by a handful of individual states at a
time when the capital markets are becoming more
international," said Ronald Gilson, an expert on corporate
governance at Stanford Law School. "The effect of it is to
leave decisions about share voting largely to individual
state law."
   Washington lawyer Richard Phillips said he expected
several companies to seek multiple classes of voting stock
"as the hostile takeover comes back into vogue." But he added
that the SEC certainly would appeal the decision. "No way
they'll leave this one alone," he said.
   SEC market regulation director Richard Ketchum called on
the exchanges to adopt uniform 19c4-type rules. "There's
always been a wide degree of consensus {among the exchanges
and the NASD} that there should be voting rights rules," he
said. "I hope that staring into the vacuum, they will
respond."
   One potential benefactor of the ruling may be "white
knights," investors who are brought in by companies to
protect against hostile bids. In the past few years, those
investors weren't able to demand better voting terms before
making their investments. That could change, said Meredith
Brown, the head of mergers and acquisitions at Debevoise &amp;
Plimpton. "This might open up the possibility of voting
arrangements" favorable to white knights, he said.
   Arthur Fleischer, a takeover lawyer at Fried Frank Harris
Shriver &amp; Jacobson, agreed. "Assuming you can justify it from
a corporate point of view, you are no longer restricted by
19c4 to have a proportional voting test," he said.
   But he added that he thinks the court ruling is "more
symbolic than practical." Except in certain specific cases,
he said, he doubts shareholders would approve multiple
classes.
   ---
   James A. White in New York contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
