<HL>
   Tax Report:
   A Special Summary and Forecast
   Of Federal and State Tax
   Developments
   ----
   By Scott R. Schmedel
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)
</IN>
<GV>
INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS)
</GV>
<LP>
   PREPAID-TUITION TRUSTS press the IRS in court and in
private for exemption.
   At least a dozen states are working on plans to help
parents finance college costs with prepaid contracts made
while a child is young. Innovator Michigan has amassed over
$350 million from over 40,000 contracts. But backers say the
programs' growth is being stifled by an IRS ruling that the
Michigan Education Trust must pay annual corporate taxes on
its earnings, in addition to the deferred taxes that students
will pay as gains are withdrawn for tuition. So Michigan and
Ohio are taking the offensive.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Michigan's trust paid its first taxes for fiscal 1988.
Last month, it sued in federal court for a refund on
constitutional and other grounds, arguing it performs an
exempt essential government function for the state.
Meanwhile, the Ohio Tuition Trust is urging the IRS to
reverse itself and rule that the plans are exempt essential
functions and is lobbying the White House and Congress for
support. Ohio hopes to get an IRS ruling by next fall.
   Ohio figures taxes add 10-15% to the price of its tuition
contract.
                                                                                                       

   THE IRS GEARS UP to clamp down on filers that don't give
IDs to banks.
   The 1983 tax act requires financial institutions that make
interest, dividend, and other nonwage payments to report
recipients' Social Security or other identification numbers
to the IRS. Recipients that don't supply numbers are subject
to a 20% withholding tax; payers that don't use due diligence
to get correct numbers are subject to penalty. But in working
out the procedures, the IRS repeatedly has delayed the
enforcement program.
   Now the IRS says it is ready to crack down. It is about to
send to payers lists of customers for which the payers' 1988
reports lacked numbers or had faulty ones. Within 60 days,
payers must certify that they have exercised due diligence.
Later this year, the IRS adds, it will inform payers of
discrepancies on 1989 reports. Then the payers must notify
the customers that the 20% withholding will begin if they
don't supply correct numbers within 30 days.
                                                                                                       

   A BIZARRE VICTORY over the IRS ends with a financial
setback.
   Thomas J. Smith, once an Illinois state tax official
handling liaison with the IRS, won the victory in January
1989. As we reported, he hadn't filed federal returns for two
years. IRS District Director Ira Loeb informed Smith's boss;
Smith later lost his job. He sued the U.S. for illegal
disclosure of taxpayer data. U.S. Judge Mills ruled that Loeb
had ignored procedures meant to protect taxpayer privacy,
making the U.S. liable for damages. The judge scheduled a
further trial to determine the amount.
   Smith sought $6 million in compensatory and punitive
damages. But earlier this year, Judge Mills said the illegal
disclosure didn't cause Smith's discharge and awarded only
$1,000 and certain costs, as prescribed for the federal-law
violation. Smith's lawyer, whose fee was contingent on the
outcome, spent 1,000 hours and $18,735 of his own money on
the case. Now, in a "postscript," the judge says Smith hasn't
met the narrow standard for winning legal fees.
   Further, only a small share of the lawyer's expenses
qualify for recovery.
                                                                                                       

   VISITORS TO CANADA are to get fast rebates of the 7% goods
and services tax due to take effect Jan. 1 if the Canadian
Senate approves. Besides giving rebates by mail, Revenue
Canada will authorize duty-free shops to issue instant cash
rebates of certain hotel and merchandise taxes.
                                                                                                       

   HIDDEN INCOME that the self-employed omit from Schedule C
of personal returns accounts for 40% of the personal tax gap,
the IRS figures. Now it's extending to 1988 and 1989 returns
a special Schedule C audit program that has covered 1983-87
returns reporting receipts exceeding $100,000.
                                                                                                       

   WIPE OUT GRAFFITI, says the California state Senate. It
adopts a bill that would permit the creation of special
districts to tax marking substances and applicators to pay
for the removal of graffiti in public places. The bill goes
next to the state Assembly.
                                                                                                       

   MULTINATIONALS LOBBY to overturn IRS rules on state-tax
deductions.
   States are barred from taxing corporate income earned
beyond their borders, but many use formulas for taxable
income that the IRS says result in taxes attributable to
income from foreign sources. After more than a decade of
wrestling with the issue, the IRS in 1988 proposed rules
requiring multinationals to allocate certain state taxes to
foreign income, thus denying deductions from U.S. income.
Companies say they are caught between state and IRS
positions.
   The companies say the rules increase their costs,
especially in comparison with foreign concerns operating in
the U.S. So they have mounted a lobbying campaign for two
bills -- H.R. 4512, backed by Rep. Thomas (R., Calif.) and
others, and S. 2584, entered by Sen. Boren (D., Okla.) and
others. The bills would let companies allocate all deductions
for state and local income and franchise taxes to U.S.
income. The lobbyists include the U.S. Chamber of Commerce
and several industry associations.
   The Multistate Tax Commission supports the bills on behalf
of 23 states.
                                                                                                       

   BRIEFS: To pamper the environment, Wisconsin exempts cloth
diapers and diaper services from sales tax, but not
disposable diapers. . . . Texas has no income tax. It adds
other distinctions with new law to reform education
financing: A 15-cent rise to 41 cents a pack gives it the
highest state cigarette levy. Its 6.25% sales tax becomes the
highest in the 15 southern states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0072
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0072.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   House Bill Introduced
   To Give SEC Power
   Over Index Futures
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
COMMODITY FUTURES TRADING COMMISSION (CFT)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Two House members introduced legislation
that would switch oversight of stock-index futures to the
Securities and Exchange Commission from the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission.
   The bill was introduced at the administration's request by
Reps. John Dingell (D., Mich.) and Norman Lent (R., N.Y.),
the ranking members of the Energy and Commerce Committee,
which oversees the SEC.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The bill would give the SEC the power to regulate
stock-index futures, which allow investors to bet on the
movement of a basket of stocks without buying the actual
securities. The bill also would create federal regulation of
futures margins, the good-faith money needed to trade.
Currently, margins are set by the commodities exchanges and
can be changed by the CFTC only in an emergency.
   The legislators haven't taken a formal position on the
proposal, a committee spokesman said. The legislation is
supported by SEC Chairman Richard Breeden and Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady, but it is strongly opposed by CFTC
Chairman Wendy Gramm, the futures industry, and members of
the House and Senate agriculture committees.
   In a statement, Mr. Dingell said that the complex
legislation warranted "careful, thorough and detailed
hearings" and that his committee intends to begin the process
as soon as possible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0071
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0071.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Rule of Law:
   What's New in Greenwich Village? Private Property Rights
   ----
   By L. Gordon Crovitz
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
LODGING, HOTELS, MOTELS, LODGES, CAMPGROUNDS (LOD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Here's what Jerrold Ziman got when he bought a $280,000
four-story house in Manhattan: an 11-by-13-foot
bedroom-kitchen-dining-living room and six years in court. He
made a mistake. He assumed the law would protect his property
rights.
   New York's housing market has long been the standard model
for Econ 101 lessons on how rent control leads to housing
shortages, tenants who can't afford to move and landlords who
can't afford to keep up buildings. Abstract principles are
hard reality for the Ziman family.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   When Jerrold and Ellen Ziman moved from Los Angeles to New
York with their two young children, they found a small town
house on quaint Minetta Street in Greenwich Village. The
200-year-old house had been divided into small apartments,
and three were occupied by rent-control tenants. The Zimans
planned to make it a one-family home again.
   Their nightmare began soon after they bought the house in
February 1984. At the time, owners could leave the rental
market and evict tenants if they planned to occupy the
property themselves. The Zimans asked the state housing
regulators to start the eviction process.
   But in June 1984, New York changed the rules. A new law
said that tenants who had lived in apartments for more than
20 years could not be evicted just because the owner wanted
to occupy his property. Instead, owners would have to prove
"undue hardship," meaning an annual return of less than 8.5%.
The two tenants in the Ziman house pay regulated monthly
rents of $159 and $180, a fraction of the going market rate
or the $20,000 annual expense of maintaining the rental
units.
   So proving hardship should have been easy, but it wasn't.
It took two audits over several years for bureaucrats in the
rent-control agency eventually to admit the Zimans were
suffering financial hardship. Then the state concocted a
bizarre new argument to deny the eviction request. The Zimans
should lose, the agency argued, because they were motivated
chiefly by the desire to occupy their house, not chiefly by
the bankrupting economic losses.
   Lawyers for the Zimans said this was unconstitutional and
absurd. "They have lost the ability to exclude strangers from
their house, they have been forced to become landlords and
they have been required to bear a hugely disproportionate
share of the costs" of rent control.
   After years of hearings, litigation and appeals, New
York's highest court two weeks ago ruled for the Zimans. A
one-page opinion found "unrefuted evidence of hardship." The
court ruling means the housing agency must begin eviction
proceedings against the tenants, but the agency hasn't acted
yet.
   The Zimans eventually should be able to make a home of
their house, but the cost has been enormous. The family has
lived in what they assumed would be temporary quarters of an
apartment in the house of less than 350 square feet-smaller
than the typical hotel room. In 1986, they got access to
another 350-square feet on another floor, where their
adolescent son now sleeps.
   Mr. Ziman, who jokes that he became a "jailhouse lawyer,"
gave up his career in entertainment for his newly found
specialty, real estate. He has legal bills of $100,000, which
would be much more without voluntary legal help from two
free-market public-interest groups, the Competitive
Enterprise Institute in Washington and the Pacific Legal
Foundation in California. CEI lawyer Sam Kazman, who handled
much of the litigation, calls this case "a small step for the
Zimans, one giant step for Manhattankind."
   Mr. Kazman plans to file a further lawsuit that might
teach bureaucrats a lesson. Recent U.S. Supreme Court cases
say that the Constitution's Fifth Amendment takings clause
entitles people to reimbursement for even temporary takings
of their property through unlawful government action. The
Zimans want payments from New York for the years of lost use
of their house. The state already lost a takings case to
owners of unlawfully regulated single-room-occupancy
buildings.
   Getting housing regulators to think twice about giving
owners the runaround would help many landlords who can't
afford legal help. An Arthur D. Little study in 1985 found
that most landlords owned one building, had incomes of
between $10,000 and $40,000 -- 30% had incomes less than
$20,000 -- and were immigrants. Who else would be naive
enough to invest in residential apartments in New York?
   Tenants tend to be from a different class. Rent-controlled
apartments are mostly in middle- and upper-class
neighborhoods. The Zimans say one of their holdout tenants
goes on an opera tour of Italy every summer. In his recent
book, "The Excluded Americans: Homelessness and Housing
Policies," William Tucker disclosed several regulated sweet
rents in a city where $1,000 is market rent for a standard
one-bedroom apartment:
   Mayor David Dinkins pays $711.99 for a three-bedroom
apartment in a middle-class development. When he was mayor,
Ed Koch paid $411.49 for a one-bedroom apartment in Greenwich
Village. A former housing-court judge, Jay Stuart Dankberg,
paid $75.15 for a two-bedroom near Gramercy Park. Among
apartments overlooking Central Park are those of Manfred
Ohrenstein, Democratic leader in the state Senate ($2,070.67
for 11 rooms); Mia Farrow ($2,272.43 for 11 rooms); and
Alistair Cooke ($1,357.66 for eight rooms).
   Token rents and high costs at the lower end of the market
help explain why some 1,500 units of housing are simply
abandoned in the city every month. State legislators issued a
report in 1987 entitled "Bleak House" of how hyperregulation
causes "hardship for thousands of people every year and in
the most extreme cases directly contributes to displacement
and homelessness."
   An upstate legislator last week introduced a bill that
would end rent control for any family with an income of
$100,000. A vicious circle makes a political solution
unlikely-rent control causes a limited supply of housing
causes higher market prices causes winners in the
rent-control game to dig in their heels.
   Indeed, the Zimans say some of their friends are
ambivalent about their victory because they can't imagine
life without their own rent-controlled apartments. "My
friends in New York just don't understand that a free market
could get them better housing at a better price," Mrs. Ziman,
a pre-school teacher, says.
   Economics aside, Mr. Ziman says he's discovered that rent
control creates a perverse mentality that sounds a lot like
what we recently called Soviet-bloc thinking. "Rent control
makes thieves of normal people," he says. "The city and state
undermine common honesty and integrity by allowing a system
built on a few winners and many losers of their own
property."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0070
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0070.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   U.S. Economy Leads Japan -- but for How Long?
   ----
   By Alan Murray
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Ask Americans what nation has the strongest overall
economy, and they'll tell you Japan. Ask Japanese the same
question, and they'll say the United States.
   Who's right?
</LP>
<TEXT>
   By most measures, the U.S. remains the world's economic
powerhouse. Its annual output is nearly twice that of Japan.
And while the Japanese may be the leaders in many important
manufacturing industries, U.S. businesses remain, overall,
the most productive in the world.
   To be sure, the Japanese have in recent years reported a
higher income per person than Americans. But that's a
statistical fluke, due largely to the dollar's decline since
1985. Income in Japan is higher only if the Japanese exchange
all their money for dollars and spend it overseas. If they
spend money in their own country, the advantage is quickly
devoured by exorbitant prices for housing and other goods.
Adjusted for local purchasing power, the average Japanese
earns only three-quarters as much as the average American.
   But while the U.S. remains in the lead, that lead is
rapidly narrowing, and many economists believe it may
disappear over the next decade.
   Hisao Kanamori, chairman of the Japan Center for Economic
Research, is one of the leading Japanese optimists. Sitting
in his corner office in downtown Tokyo, a pipe in his hand,
he confidently predicts Japan will grow at roughly a 5%
annual rate during the 1990s, while the U.S. grows at about a
3% rate. The result: By the year 2000, Japan will have an
economy roughly the same size as America's, and its
per-person income will be nearly double that in the U.S.
   That's a stunning prediction, but it isn't without reason.
Many economists see savings and investment as the engines of
future growth, and in both areas the Japanese continue to
beat the U.S. hands down. Last year, for instance, Japanese
households saved nearly 17% of their after-tax income,
compared to just over 5% in the U.S. And Japanese businesses
had gross investment equalling 26% of the nation's output,
compared with 15% in the U.S.
   Moreover, Japan's edge in many high-tech industries will
help fuel its growth in the coming decade, Mr. Kanamori says.
"The things that Japan is strong at are the things of the
1990s," he notes.
   Official estimates put Japanese growth over the next 10
years considerably lower. And lately, in the wake of turmoil
in the Tokyo stock market, some commentators have begun to
argue that the Japanese miracle is over. "My perception is
that Japan is now at its peak in terms of industrial power,"
says Akira Kojima, an editorial writer for the Nihon Keizai
Shimbun, the major Japanese business daily.
   Eager to calm American fears, Japanese government
officials also push the notion that Japan has peaked --
especially when they are speaking to overseas visitors. The
savings rate is slowly declining, they say, and young people
lack the vigorous work ethic of their elders. Moreover, a
rapidly aging population will be a drag on the economy in the
coming years.
   "The Japanese days are over," says Tadashi Nakamae, an
economic consultant who is among the most pessimistic. He
says Japanese manufacturers will soon find they have
"invested too much," and as a result face excess capacity.
And they won't be able to sell their products overseas, he
says, without competing with their own overseas subsidiaries.
   Mr. Kanamori dismisses such concerns. "The government's
position is too conservative," he says. "The government is
always too conservative." As for the problem of an aging
population, the 66-year-old economist says that can be eased
by letting people work longer.
   If history is any guide, Japan's anxiety over its economic
future may prove one of its great strengths. The Japanese
have always worried that their economic strength is a fragile
blossom, ready to blow away with the wind. As a result,
they've worked harder to preserve it.
   During the oil-price spikes of the 1970s, for instance,
the Japanese fretted that their oil-dependent economy had met
its match. But the oil crisis only prompted them to make
their manufacturing industries more fuel-efficient.
   And when the yen rose sharply in the mid-1980s, making it
harder for the Japanese to sell their exports around the
world, they again worried about the beating their
manufacturers would take. But in the end, after cost-cutting
and new productivity campaigns, the Japanese emerged stronger
than ever.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0069
</DOCNO>
