<HL>
   Who's News:
   Fundamentalist Picked
   By Southern Baptists
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   NEW ORLEANS -- For the 12th consecutive year, a
fundamentalist was elected president of the Southern Baptist
Convention.
   At the denomination's annual meeting, the Rev. Morris
Chapman of Wichita Falls, Texas, received 21,471 votes, or
57.7% of the total, to defeat the Rev. Daniel Vestal of
Dunwoody, Ga., who received 15,753 votes, or 42.3%. Mr.
Vestal was the candidate of the convention's moderate
faction, which has accused the fundamentalists of launching a
purge of Southern Baptist seminaries and other organizations,
targeting persons who don't accept a literal interpretation
of the Bible.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A recent Page One story in The Wall Street Journal
described how the struggle between the two factions had led
to a decline in active membership, seminary enrollment and
appointment of missionaries in the denomination, which claims
to be the largest Protestant body in the U.S.
   A total of 38,241 clergy and lay people registered at the
New Orleans convention, making the gathering the third
largest in Southern Baptist history, after the 1985
convention in Dallas and the 1986 convention in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0047
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0047.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   Stafford Is Removed
   As Egg-Division Head
   Of Michael Foods Inc.
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MIKL WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   MINNEAPOLIS --Michael Foods Inc. has removed John M.
Stafford as head of its egg division, which represents about
half the company's sales.
   A former chief executive officer of Pillsbury Co., Mr.
Stafford, 53 years old, had served in that position only a
few months. He remains executive vice president and a
director of the company.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Stafford, who confirmed his removal from the post,
declined further comment beyond saying there were several
projects he may be assigned to. A Michael Foods spokesman
declined to discuss the unannounced change, saying the
company doesn't comment on personnel matters.
   Succeeding Mr. Stafford will be Daniel Gardner, 65,
chairman of Milton G. Waldbaum Co., a Wakefield, Neb., egg
producer, which Michael recently acquired.
   The management change came as a rival concern, Papetti
High-Grade Egg Products Co. of Elizabeth, N.J., confirmed it
is supplying a pasteurized egg product to Burger King Corp.,
the fast-food chain unit of Grand Metropolitan PLC. Burger
King is believed to be the largest customer for Michael's
Easy Eggs ultra-pasteurized product.
</TEXT>
