<HL>
   International:
   Japan's Surplus
   In Trade Shrank
   Slightly in May
   ---
   But Some Economists Say
   Measure Might Widen
   Again in a Few Months
   ----
   By Yumiko Ono
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Japan's May trade surplus narrowed slightly from
the year before, but economists said the rate of decline is
slowing and the surplus may start to expand again in a few
months.
   The Finance Ministry said that the May surplus, measured
when goods pass through customs, dropped 16.6% to $3.13
billion from $3.76 billion a year earlier. In April, by
contrast, the surplus fell a sharp 51.4% from the year
before. Exports in May declined 0.9%, to $21.52 billion from
$21.7 billion. Imports grew at a slower pace than recently
posted, rising 2.4% to $18.38 billion from $17.95 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The trade surplus with the U.S. also narrowed, falling
11.4% to $2.44 billion from $2.76 billion in the previous
year. Exports to the U.S. dropped 4.5% to $6.82 billion, but
imports also fell 0.2% to $4.38 billion.
   Ministry officials said that although Japan's global
surplus continued to shrink, "the amount of decline seems to
have narrowed." One reason for the slowdown, the official
explained, was falling oil prices. Higher crude-oil prices
last year made an important contribution to import growth. In
May, however, crude-oil prices dropped from the year before
to $16.79 per barrel from $18.02 a year earlier. So although
the volume of crude oil imports rose 3.1% to 16,200
kiloliters, imports in value terms dropped 4% to $1.71
billion.
   Economists said the lower value of the yen against the
dollar was also putting a brake on the pace of decline in the
surplus. The ministry calculated that the dollar's average
exchange rate in May was 156.98 yen compared with 133.88 yen
a year ago. A weaker yen makes imports more expensive. At the
same time, the exchange rate makes the price of exports more
competitive in the world market.
   Although the dollar-denominated value of exports dropped,
the volume of exports actually grew 8.4%, said Kazuko Mizuno,
an economist at Baring Securities (Japan) Ltd. Export growth
was especially high for motorcycles, rising 32.2% to $150.67
million, and ships, increasing 30.9% to $319.1 million.
Exports of office equipment, another area in which Japanese
companies are very competitive, also rose 8.9% to $1.54
billion.
   Import volume, on the other hand, grew at a slower pace of
6.5%, compared with the average pace of 7.8% in 1989.
Although economists expect the surplus to continue narrowing
for a few more months, "this can't go on forever," said
Takayuki Tanaka, an economist for Japan's Long Term Credit
Bank. "The drop in the growth of imports may lead to an
expansion in the surplus," added Ms. Mizuno of Baring
Securities, possibly starting in August or September.
   That would bring additional pressure to bear on the
Japanese government from the U.S. Recently, Japanese
officials have sparked a debate by asserting that although
Japan is committed to reducing its trade surplus further,
retaining an overall external surplus that allows Japan to
remain a capital exporter is essential to a healthy world
economy.
   On a seasonally adjusted basis, the overall trade surplus
grew 6.9% in May from April to $3.41 billion from $3.19
billion. Adjusted exports grew 2.2%, to $21.48 billion from
$21.03 billion, while adjusted imports also grew 1.3%, to
$18.07 billion from $17.84 billion. Adjusted figures on a yen
basis showed a wider increase, with the surplus in May rising
37.2% from April to 656 billion yen from 479 billion yen.
   In trade with the U.S., Japan's exports dropped in a
number of areas, in part because Japanese companies' American
factories supplied more and more U.S. demand, said Mr. Tanaka
of Long Term Credit Bank. In particular, exports of engines
fell 32.2% to $193.87 million from the year before, while
exports of semiconductors dropped 19.7% to $299.95 million.
   The trade surplus with the European Community narrowed
26.4% to $1.2 billion. Exports increased 7.1% to $4.07
billion, while motorcycle exports rose 52.4% to $89.9
million. Meanwhile, imports from the EC rose 32.3% to $2.87
billion. The growth in imports was seen in cars, mainly from
West Germany, which doubled to $535 million. Imports of
alcoholic beverages rose 34.5% to $114.7 million, and Japan's
purchases of art from the EC countries doubled, reaching
$157.1 million in May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0024
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0024.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   AT&amp;T Signs Up
   Million Accounts
   For Credit Card
   ----
   By John J. Keller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   T
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., which
unveiled its credit card only 79 days ago, said it has signed
up one million accounts for the card so far and plans to be
among the nation's five largest issuers by the end of 1991.
   The million-account mark, which translates into 1.7
million card holders, is more than three times as many
accounts as experts had predicted up to this point for the
AT&amp;T Universal card, which comes as either a Visa or
MasterCard and also serves as a calling card.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The success of AT&amp;T's card hasn't gone unnoticed by four
of the nation's largest bank-card issuers, which have filed
complaints with federal and state authorities, challenging
the card's legality.
   "We are more than double where we expected to be by this
time in terms of accounts," said Paul Kahn, president of AT&amp;T
Universal Card Services Corp. "And revenue in the first month
was more than four times ahead."
   In fact, he said, card holders have made more than $100
million in purchases, and those revenues don't include
long-distance call charges.
   Analysts have pegged the card's success so far to a free
lifetime membership to any card holder who signs up this
year. AT&amp;T is also offering a 10% discount on all
long-distance calls made with the card.
   Employees have also put in long hours, said Mr. Kahn. "Our
people have been working six and seven-day weeks, more than I
would have liked, to book this business."
   AT&amp;T joined forces in March with Synovus Financial Corp.,
a Columbus, Ga., bank holding company, to distribute the AT&amp;T
Universal Card and process card accounts through Synovus's
Total Systems Services Inc. Another Synovus subsidiary,
Universal Bank, issues the cards and handles billing on card
transactions. AT&amp;T owns a small stake in Universal and buys
its credit-card receivables.
   Last month, Citicorp, Chase Manhattan Corp., BankAmerica
Corp. and MNC Financial Corp. asked the Federal Reserve
Board, the Federal Communications Commission and the Georgia
State Banking Department to examine whether AT&amp;T's venture
violates banking and communications law.
   The banks have charged that Universal Bank is controlled
by AT&amp;T and that the communications giant is therefore
violating federal banking laws that forbid commercial and
industrial companies from owning commercial banks. The banks
also claim that Universal is really a funding vehicle for an
unregulated affiliate, AT&amp;T. They also allege that the bank
is grossly undercapitalized, given its $3 million in capital
and ambitions to reach millions of customers.
   What's more, the banks have complained to the FCC that the
10% discount on calls amounts to "predatory pricing" against
other communications providers and is a price cut the FCC
hasn't authorized under its normal tariff system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0023
</DOCNO>
