<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0013
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0013.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   GORBACHEV PROPOSED a looser federation of sovereign Soviet
states.
   In an attempt to hold together a splintering Soviet Union,
the Kremlin leader told the presidents of all 15 republics to
nominate representatives and prepare drafts for a union "that
would have elements of a federation, a confederation or some
such pluralistic relationship." Gorbachev also met separately
with the leaders of Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia, the first
such talks since he termed their independence bids illegal,
and progress was reported toward ending the impasse.
Meanwhile, Russia approved a resolution proclaiming its
sovereignty. Gorbachev also indicated flexibility on a united
Germany's membership in the Warsaw Pact and NATO.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet parliament passed a bill to guarantee press
freedom and eliminate censorship, with officials facing
charges if they hamper journalists.
   ---
   Firefighters conquered a blaze aboard the Mega Borg oil
tanker in the Gulf of Mexico. The Coast Guard said it was
encouraged by the progress and that chances are now slim that
the disabled ship will sink. However, crude oil continues to
pour out of the vessel and authorities said a major spill is
still a possibility.
   ---
   The Senate Ethics Committee opened hearings into the
financial dealings of Sen. Dave Durenberger. A special
counsel to the committee recommended that the Minnesota
Republican be denounced by the Senate for "knowingly engaging
in unethical conduct which has brought dishonor and disrepute
to this institution."
   ---
   Bush said he hadn't decided whether to break off talks
with the Palestine Liberation Organization, but he demanded
that the Arab group condemn a May 30 terrorist raid on Israel
by one of the PLO's factions. Secretary of State Baker
earlier stated that the Arab organization's statements so far
"have fallen short of the mark."
   ---
   The Senate failed by a margin of two votes to override
Bush's veto of an Amtrak-authorization bill in a hard-fought
battle over a regulatory provision that provoked lobbying
from unions and the railroad industry. The vote followed an
intense administration campaign headed by Transportation
Secretary Skinner.
   ---
   Medical researchers reported that a comprehensive
education program for premature, underweight babies that
begins just after birth can significantly improve the
infants' chances for productive lives. More than 250,000
babies are born prematurely each year in the U.S.
   ---
   Algerians cast ballots in the country's first contested
elections since French rule ended in 1962. The interior
minister said Moslem fundamentalists were set to score an
upset victory against the ruling National Liberation Front,
based on initial results. Eleven parties vied in municipal
and provincial races in the North African nation.
   ---
   The House defied a White House veto threat, sending Bush a
bill that would free federal workers for considerably more
off-the-job political activity. The House voted to adopt a
version of the legislation the Senate approved last month for
liberalizing restrictions set by the 51-year-old Hatch Act.
   ---
   Liberian rebels began talks in Sierra Leone with officials
of the Monrovia government. Members of the Liberian Council
of Churches are mediating the negotiations to end the West
African nation's tribal war.
   ---
   The World Health Organization said the rapid spread of the
AIDS virus in developing nations means the disease will be
more widespread in the next century than previously thought.
WHO said its current projection of up to 20 million people
infected with AIDS by the year 2000 is a minimum that the
agency expects to revise upward.
   ---
   Soviet and U.S. negotiators resumed formal talks in Geneva
on proposed deep reductions in long-range nuclear weapons.
The chief Soviet negotiator said he expected to reach an
agreement this year on a Strategic Arms Reduction Talks pact.
   ---
   A cease-fire accord was reached in Sri Lanka between the
government and Tamil rebels. Declaration of the truce, to
take effect today, followed two days of renewed fighting in
the northeastern part of the Indian Ocean island. The
minority Tamils are seeking political autonomy, claiming
discrimination by the majority Sinhalese.
   ---
   Mozambique delegations arrived in neighboring Malawi for
peace talks. Representatives of Mozambique's left-wing
government and rebel leaders were to begin their first direct
discussions aimed at ending a civil war that has claimed
hundreds of thousands of lives during the past 13 years in
the southeast African nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
