<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0010
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0010.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   AN APPEALS COURT struck down the SEC's "one share, one
vote" rule, a move that could reshape the way some companies
protect themselves from takeovers. The federal panel said the
SEC had overstepped its authority and had entered corporate
governance, an area traditionally determined by state law.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis has raised about $1.7 billion from
investors to inject into RJR Nabisco to bolster RJR's sagging
bonds, according to people close to the proposed transaction.
   ---
   Stocks surged with the Dow Jones industrials climbing
40.85 points to 2933.42, less than two points below the
record high set June 4. U.S. bonds slipped a bit. The dollar
rose against the mark but fell against the yen.
   ---
   The balance of payments narrowed to $22.9 billion in the
first quarter, its lowest level in six years. Analysts said
strong growth overseas boosted exports, while sluggish growth
in the U.S. slowed demand for imports.
                                                                                                       

   Japan's trade surplus contracted in May, but economists
said it may expand again in a few months.
   ---
   The FDIC isn't likely to permit banks to underwrite
insurance despite a new Delaware law that permits such
activity, Chairman Seidman said.
                                                                                                       

   Bank earnings fell 14% in the first quarter from a year
earlier. Seidman warned of growing problems in Midwest and
Northwest real-estate loans.
   ---
   Milken's planned appearance before a House subcommittee
this summer may be blocked, if prosecutors and regulators
have their way. They don't want the ex-Drexel official to
testify before he is sentenced Oct. 1.
   ---
   The Big Board's proposal for trading halts drew many
complaints from traders, investors and executives. The plan
was recommended after a study of ways to curb market
volatility.
   ---
   NBC will slash the audience-size guarantees it makes to
advertisers, joining rival Capital Cities/ABC. But both say
A.C. Nielsen figures showing that many viewers deserted TV in
the first quarter are inaccurate.
   ---
   Chrysler and Renault agreed to terminate their venture to
build a new mini-sport utility vehicle.
   Chrysler may be seeking Dollar Rent-a-Car, one of the few
big independent car rental firms left.
   ---
   ITT plans to sell part of its 37% stake in Alcatel N.V. to
its partner in a European telecommunications joint venture
for $640 million. Proceeds will be used primarily to buy back
stock.
   ---
   American Express hopes to raise $825 million through a
public offering of 27 million new shares. Nippon Life will
buy about 10 million of them.
   ---
   A former Chicago Merc member said orders from the trading
firm of exchange head Leo Melamed got special handling, at
times forcing local traders to take losses on trades.
   ---
   Bank of New York named Alan R. Griffith president of its
flagship bank. Mr. Griffith, a senior executive vice
president, had been a dark horse.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 157,100,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2933.42, up 40.85; transportation 1208.76, up 6.75; utilities
215.04, up 1.82.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3421.35, off
1.95.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.06, up 0.36; spot
index 131.63, up 0.07.
   Dollar: 154.55 yen, off 0.22; 1.6965 marks, up 0.0035.
</TEXT>
