<HL>
   Royal Bank of Canada
   Agrees to Purchase
   International Trust
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   T.RY
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   MONTREAL -- Royal Bank of Canada said it agreed to acquire
International Trust Co., even though Canadian legislation
doesn't permit banks to buy trust concerns, which are similar
to U.S. thrifts.
   The purchase price wasn't disclosed. International Trust
is wholly owned by closely held International Trustco Inc.,
based in Toronto. It has about 80 employees, and at the end
of 1989 it was administering on behalf of clients assets of
about 3 billion Canadian dollars (US$2.56 billion).
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Jim MacKay, a Royal Bank vice president, said the purchase
would be completed as soon as proposed changes to Canada's
Bank Act permit such a transaction. But the new rules
probably won't be introduced in the federal legislature until
this fall, he said. In the meantime, Royal Bank will be able
to refer its customers seeking trust services to
International Trust. Trust services include custodial fees
for pension funds, trustee, administration and record-keeping
services for group savings plans, securities lending and
pooled investment funds.
   Canada's banks have been awaiting further deregulation of
the financial-services sector since they were permitted in
1987 to own securities dealers. One of their goals is to
expand into businesses that generate fee income, such as the
trust business and insurance. Although current regulations
prohibit banks from owning insurance companies, several of
them have established links with insurance companies by
referring their bank clients to them.
   Mr. MacKay said that by agreeing to buy International
Trust as soon as permitted by law, rather than building the
business from the ground up, Royal Bank will save three years
in the development of its trust operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900613-0006
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900613-0006.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   NRC Proposes Fine
   Of $160,000 for 3M
   For Safety Violations
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   MMM
</CO>
<IN>
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Nuclear Regulatory Commission proposed
fining Minnesota Mining &amp; Manufacturing Co. $160,000 for the
company's alleged "willful violations" of NRC safety and
reporting requirements.
   The company has 30 days to respond to the proposed
penalty.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The regulatory agency's findings relate to an air-ionizer
3M manufactured in the mid-1980s. By early 1988, the NRC
ordered a recall of some models of the ionizers, which
contained microscopic metal spheres that held particles of a
radioactive source, polonium 210.
   The recall was ordered after agency investigators found
that the ionizers, or static-removing devices, leaked
radioactivity at some customers' industrial plants. The
leakage was at levels so low that it didn't represent a
significant health hazard, and consumer products made at the
affected plants showed no contamination.
   The company later expanded the recall to include all
ionizer models containing the radioactive material, and
halted those models' production.
   The company said it is "surprised by the size of the
proposed penalty," given the company's cooperation and
compliance with NRC's requests. It is "studying the specifics
of the allegations and will respond."
   The NRC said it found seven violations. Among them, it
said 3M failed to make sure customers would use the devices
in "acceptable environments." It also said the company didn't
check returned ionizers for surface contamination, a process
that would identify any leaking devices that should be
classified unacceptable.
   The agency said 3M also failed to tell customers how the
leaking ionizers should be handled, and to provide the NRC
with complete reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
